================================================================================
Licensing of the distributed binaries
================================================================================

This project's own source is Apache-2.0. The dependency graph of the binaries it
distributes is almost, but not quite, clean of copyleft — here is exactly where
it stands.

The `sc-*` Substrate client crates are GPL-3.0-or-later WITH
Classpath-exception-2.0. The node links 40 of them. The Classpath exception
exists precisely to permit linking them from a differently-licensed binary, so
they impose no copyleft on this project. Nothing to resolve there.

`frame-benchmarking-cli` is used only by `node/src/benchmarking.rs`, which is
gated behind the `runtime-benchmarks` feature. It is therefore declared
`optional` in `node/Cargo.toml` and is NOT in the default dependency graph. This
matters: left non-optional it drags in 150 further crates — the `polkadot-*`,
`staging-xcm*` and `tracing-gum*` trees, via `cumulus-*` — 17 of which are
strict `GPL-3.0-only` with no exception. Gating it keeps them out of the shipped
binary entirely.

That leaves exactly one strict-copyleft crate anywhere in the graph:

  `pallet-skip-feeless-payment` (v23.0.0), a direct dependency of the runtime.

Its published crate metadata says `license = "GPL-3.0-only"`. Every one of its
source files says otherwise:

    // Copyright (C) Parity Technologies (UK) Ltd.
    // SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0

The metadata is an upstream packaging slip, not a deliberate relicense. The
crate's manifest declares `license.workspace = true`, inheriting the
polkadot-sdk workspace default of `GPL-3.0-only`; 238 crates under `substrate/`
explicitly override that default and 15 — including this one — forget to. Its
own directory siblings, `transaction-payment` and `transaction-payment/asset-
tx-payment`, both override it correctly.

We read the Apache-2.0 file headers as the operative grant, and have reported
the manifest bug upstream. We are flagging it here rather than quietly relying
on it, because it is the kind of thing you would rather hear from us than
discover from `cargo metadata`. If your own compliance process needs the
manifest and the headers to agree, this is the one place in the tree where they
do not.
